Then, and as suggested in \autoref{experimental:design:fig}, subjects were randomly assigned the order in which they saw the direct question and the list experiment. Eventually, all subjects answered both the direct question \emph{and} the list experiment. The \hyperlink{direct.question}{direct question} posited that there was going to be assigned at random the hypothetical possibility to do one of the illegal things mentioned in the distractor paragraph. However, and despite faking random assignment, all subjects were directly asked whether they would be interested in selling their votes. Immediately after, they answered a \hyperlink{pricing.experiment}{pricing experiment}, where they were asked for the right price for their votes.\todo{find literature on this.}

The list experiment contemplated one control (without any sensitive vote-selling item), and two treatments, each with different vote-selling prices. Since it is difficult to price a vote, based on a number of pretests, it was decided to consider an arbitrarily low (\$100) and an arbitrarily high price (\$500) delivered via two different treatments. More than being hard pricing tests, these two treatments control for (possible) different elasticities that might have interacted with individual socio-economic backgrounds, mainly income. Subjects randomly assigned to the control condition, answered the following question:

\begin{lstlisting}[frame=lrtb]
Now, you will have to type HOW MANY, if any, of the following illegal activities you might engage in, assuming you would not go to jail.

(1) steal an iPod from a large department store
(2) speed on the highway because you're late for work/school
(3) download your favorite music from the internet illegally

Type in HOW MANY (NOT WHICH), if any, of these things you would do.
\end{lstlisting}

Subjects assigned to the treatment condition answered \emph{one} the following two treatments. The ones assigned to the low price item, read and answered the following question:


\begin{lstlisting}[frame=lrtb]
Now, you will have to type HOW MANY, if any, of the following illegal activities you might engage in, assuming you would not go to jail.

(1) steal an iPod from a large department store
(2) speed on the highway because you're late for work/school
(3) sell your vote to a candidate for $100
(4) download your favorite music from the internet illegally

Type in HOW MANY (NOT WHICH), if any, of these things you would do.
\end{lstlisting}


However, the ones assigned to the high price vote-selling item, read exactly the same vignette,  with the only difference that the third item read as follows: \texttt{(3) sell your vote to a candidate for \$500}. \autoref{fig:barplot:figure:control:treatment} shows the distinct frequencies of subjects declaring how many (if any) illegal things they would do. 



