\paragraph{Data Analyses.} \emph{Would U.S. citizens sell their vote?} Following the advice of \citet{Blair2012} and \citet{Imai2014}, the list data were analyzed using a statistical multivariate approach.\footnote{\autoref{tab:regression} shows the regression table.} These analyses allow estimating the probability of selling one's vote indirectly, via the list experiment. \autoref{fig:list:analysis:social:desirability:plot} suggests that $\Sexpr{round(((socdes.p.high.low$fit[socdes.p.high.low$c.1.3=="List"][1] + socdes.p.high.low$fit[socdes.p.high.low$c.1.3=="List"][2]) / 2) * 100, 0)}$\% of the nationally representative sample would be willing to sell their vote (both in \$100 or \$500).\footnote{This probability was obtained by computing the probability of the `high' and `low' conditions, and then dividing them by two.} Since differences are not statistically significant, there are not treatment-specific price elasticities. When subjects are directly asked about selling their votes, they systematically under-report (due to social desirability bias). Particularly, around $\Sexpr{round(((socdes.p.high.low$fit[socdes.p.high.low$c.1.3=="Soc. Des."][1] + socdes.p.high.low$fit[socdes.p.high.low$c.1.3=="Soc. Des."][2]) / 2) * 100,0)}$\% of the nationally representative sample lied about it. 



